*How to read:* 

Percentage of caregivers who do not require permission to vaccinate their child. Lower values may signal decision-making barriers — interpret alongside gender, behavioural, and coverage data.

*How to read* 

- Where the % proportion of caregivers who do not need permission is low, this indicates a gender, cultural or norms related barrier to uptake
- Limited decision-making may restrict uptake.
- Improving autonomy suggests a more enabling environment.

 *Next steps* 

- Focus on populations reporting low agency or SBC exposure.
- Triangulate with behavioral and coverage data.
- Analyse by sex and geography and identify gaps
- Conduct correlation analysis to explore links with uptake.

*How to read* 

- The indicator on service experience excludes caregivers who have not attended immunization services, including those who may experience access barriers – interpret this indicator with caution.
- Where perception of the service experience is low
- Identify the most prevalent barriers at facility and community levels.
- Compare results by sex to identify disparities.
- Distinguish financial, geographic, safety, or opportunity-cost barriers.

 *Next steps* 

- Analyse by geography and sex.
- Where service experience is low, review other health system data at district and facility level to understand the specific issues for quality service delivery (e.g., stock data, HRH, outreach)
- Prioritize high-frequency barriers.
- Use correlation analysis to identify barriers most linked to under-vaccination.

*How to read* 

- Positive service experience + lower dropout suggests effective service delivery.
- Poor service experience + high dropout signals facility-level barriers.
- Positive service experience + low coverage points to external barriers (e.g., norms, confidence, gender-related).
- Wide geographic variation indicates uneven service quality and need for standardization.
- Discrepancies  require triangulation with behavioral and supply data.

 *Next steps* 

- Investigate districts with poor experience or high dropout (i.e. review other indicators, where needed conduct qualitative assessments).
- Triangulate with supply factors (e.g., vaccine availability, workforce, access to services).
- Leverage social and behavioural insights to strengthen quality of care and address service gaps.
- Implement SBC strategies where non-service barriers persist.
- Monitor trends to track improvement.

*How to read* 

- Weak social norms indicate limited community support.
- Low perception of vaccine safety indicate issues around trust and information
- Subnational variation suggests context-specific barriers.
- Consistently low indicators signal multiple demand challenges.
- Low confidence can be indicative of lack of trust in the health system.
- Variations Female–male results may reflect gender barriers.
- High demand + low coverage suggests access or service quality constraints.

 *Next steps* 

- Focus on low-performing districts.
- Triangulate with coverage and service data (e.g., stockouts, sessions planned vs delivered/cancelled, ratio of health workers to the population served).
- Strengthen confidence and social norms through targeted community engagement.
- Address gender and practical barriers.
- Monitor trends to support course correction

*How to read* 

- Compares intention with coverage to identify if gaps are driven by lack of demand for immunization
- Low intention + low coverage signals a lack of demand for immunization.
- If levels of intention are greater than coverage, this  is indicative of barriers beyond motivation (e.g., access, service experience).
- Review subnational patterns and differences across antigens to detect drop-out.

 *Next steps* 

- Analyse by geography and sex to identify underserved groups.
- Prioritize areas, groups or antigens with the largest intention–coverage gaps.
- Triangulate with other behavioral, barrier, outbreak and supply data.
- Use the raw data to conduct correlation and segmentation analysis where feasible to guide targeted action.
*Intention vs Uptake*
*Intention vs Social Norms vs Vaccine Safety*
*Service Experience vs Drop Out / Service Experience vs Coverage*
*Practical Barriers*
*Equity & Inclusion*

*Resources* 

- [Behavioural and social drivers of vaccination: tools and practical guidance for achieving high uptake](https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240049680) 
- [UNICEF Immunization Roadmap To 2030](https://www.unicef.org/documents/unicef-immunization-roadmap-2030) 
- [Gender and Immunization Global Gender Analysis Tool](https://www.unicef.org/documents/gender-immunization-global-analysis-tool) 
- [Multisectoral zero-dose strategies to improve routine immunization and other child outcome](https://www.unicef.org/documents/multisectoral-zero-dose-strategies-improve-routine-immunization-and-other-child-outcomes) 
- [Embedding Social and Behavioural Change (SBC) Approaches in National Immunization Strategies (NIS) to Promote Demand and Uptake - A supplement to NIS guidance](https://sites.google.com/view/esacreddemandtwg/guidance-and-tools) 
- [Enhancing Service Experience: A practical guide for immunization managers](https://drive.google.com/file/d/19XdAv8DHXkNyKyZwu65Wt4YJjBHgJotf/view) 
- [Quality Immunization Services: A planning guide](https://www.who.int/publications/b/57904)
